The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | T20 League part of FTP
                                                   CRICKET BRIEFS
                      
	 T20 League part of FTP
    Johannesburg: The Champions League Twenty20 has been incorporated in the International Cricket Council (ICC)s Future Tours Programme (FTP) and there will be an annual window for the Twenty20 event, Indian Premier League (IPL) commissioner Lalit Modi said.         
	I think Champions League has already been slotted in as part of the FTP, Modi told the official IPL website.         
	The BCCI vice president also felt that a tournament of IPLs magnitude also deserves a window in the ICC calendar.               
	 Anjum in
    Calcutta: The ICC has confirmed that the event technical committee of the World T20 Cup has approved Iftikhar Anjum as a replacement for Shoaib Akhtar in Pakistans squad for the tournament, which runs from June 5 to 21 in England. Shoaib was declared unfit by the PCB medical board on 21 May. Pakistan will play their first match against England at Lords on June 7.               
	 Cup Plans 
    Karachi: Pakistan team coach Intikhab Alam is confident that the sessions held by a sports psychologist with the team players will help them be mentally prepared to handle the pressure in the ICC World T20 Cup in England.               
	 Gibbs choice
    Johannesburg: Herschelle Gibbs will soon have to take a difficult decision of choosing between the Deccan Chargers and South Africa domestic T20 champions Cape Cobras for playing in the Champions League Twenty20.         
	Gibbs was part of domestic T20 winners Cobras and on Sunday, the Chargers, whom he represented, lifted the IPL trophy. IPL commissioner Lalit Modi said that it was up to Gibbs to choose his side.               
	 Majola view
    Johannesburg: The Cricket South Africa (CSA) chief Gerald Majola said that the Indian Premier League (IPL) has the potential to globalise the game and help prosper the other formats as well.         
	Internationally, it has changed the landscape of world cricket. If properly handled, the IPL concept will bring about the real globalisation of the sport for the first time, he said.               
	 Pak Stand 
    Karachi: Pakistan sports minister Pir Aftab Shah Jilani alleged that the Board of Control for Cricket in India (BCCI) of influencing the ICC to shift the World Cup 2011 cricket matches from Pakistan and deplored the BCCIs role in the issue. The minister also blamed Pakistan cricket authorities for not handling the World Cup issues properly.               
	 PCB move
    Karachi: The Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) is all set to sack as many as 250 employees in a restructuring of its organisation, to be completed by the end of May. At present we have around 544 employees in the board and the idea is to cut the expenses of the board which means that we will be laying off some employees, he said.           A STAFF REPORTER AMP; AGENCIES                                                                                                                   
